tent": "The near-\u20ac1.9 million in donations received by the Irish Red Cross in aid of the community of Creeslough following last year's devastating explosion has been hailed as a \"wonderful example\" of Irish unity during tragic times.\nThe Donegal village experienced untold tragedy on Friday, 7 October last year when an explosion at an Applegreen service station claimed the lives of 10 people, including three children.\nMany heartbreaking stories began to emerge in the wake of the disaster, detailing the ordinary, day-to-day tasks the unsuspecting victims were undertaking when in the station at that fateful moment.\nRead More: Man, 30s, dies after falling from height in tragic workplace accident in Westmeath\nJames O\u2019Flaherty (48), Jessica Gallagher (24), Martin McGill (49), Catherine O\u2019Donnell (39) and her son James Monaghan (13), Hugh Kelly (59), Martina Martin (49), Robert Garwe (50) and his daughter Shauna Flanagan Garwe (5) and Leona Harper (14) all perished in the blast.\nWhile the entire nation joined the rural northwest community in mourning the unspeakable loss, there was a national call to help those directly affected by the event.\nThe Irish Red Cross set up an emergency appeal, in conjunction with An Post and Applegreen, to provide swift financial and psychological supports to the individuals and families who were so suddenly hit by loss and hardship.\n(Image: PA)\nThe charity announced this week that it has since raised a total of almost \u20ac1.9 million in funds donated by the public. The funds raised primarily went towards emergency funding and pre-planned lump-sum payments, as well as costs associated with maintaining a constant presence in the village.\nContributors to the hefty sum include online, corporate and community event donations.\nDeirdre Garvey, Secretary General of the Irish Red Cross, said: \"As we remember those impacted by this devastating tragedy a year ago, we would like to extend our heartfelt thanks to the people a