 their initial investment back in the event of a sale. They are crucial if the sale price is not high enough to cover all the investors at the price they initially paid.\nMr Yum and me & u completed their merger last week, marking one of the first, high-profile consolidations in a tech industry where cash-burning start-ups struggle to raise fresh capital at higher valuations.\nSources said the merger ratio of the hotly contested deal was a 55-45 split, with Mr Yum owning the larger slice of the combined company. Shares in Mr Yum are now fetching $17.55 each.\nBoth loss-making companies have launched operations in the US but face a culture reluctant to use software that gives customers ways to circumvent leaving a tip to poorly paid workers.\nMr Yum and me & u are each booking about $US18 million ($28 million) in net revenue for their businesses, and have said consolidation will allow them to strip out operating and marketing costs for the lookalike businesses.\nAdvertisement\nBut the similarity of their software limits the utility of the deal, with one source familiar with the pact likening it to a \u201cshotgun wedding\u201d.\nThe union between the two rivals took several months to complete, with insiders pointing to the squabbling over which parties would share the pain of dilution: venture investors for both companies or the founders.\nNone would comment on the record for this story, which is based on several sources familiar with the transaction who spoke on condition of anonymity to preserve relationships.\nMr Yum grabbed headlines in 2021 when it completed a $US60 million capital raising at a pre-money valuation of $US250 million, which was almost 50 times annualised net revenue at the time.\nUS-based investor Tiger Global \u2013 often criticised for inflating Australian tech valuations during a very frothy year \u2013 led that round, tipping in $US25 million.\nFund manager Rajeev Gupta of Alium Capital said he is pursuing M & A options for a number of his por